<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910823-0129</DOCNO><DOCID>910823-0129.</DOCID><HL>   Technology:   Microsoft Windows Spurs   15% Rise in Software Sales</HL><DATE>08/23/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3</SO><CO>   AAPL HWP MSFT</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)SOFTWARE (SOF)</IN><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)WASHINGTON (WA)</RE><LP>   Boosted by the success of Microsoft Corp.'s Windowssoftware, North American retail software sales rose 15% inthe second quarter, a trade group said.   The Software Publishers Association, a Washington,D.C.-based trade group that represents about 800 softwareconcerns, said retail sales in North America were about $1.2billion in the quarter, up from $1.04 billion a year earlier.</LP><TEXT>   Sales of Windows applications software more than tripledin the quarter. Such products now account for 15.3% of thedomestic software market, about equal to the stake held byapplications software for Apple Computer Inc.'s Macintosh.For the first time ever, sales of DOS applications software,which still accounts for most of the market, showed a slightdecline.   Microsoft's Windows is used with DOS software, makingpersonal computers easier to use. Among other things, itallows people to operate their computers by pointing to iconswith a control-device, rather than typing in characters.   Apple is pursuing a lawsuit against Microsoft andHewlett-Packard Co., charging that they illegally copiedvisual displays that are unique to the look and feel of theMacintosh. Microsoft and Hewlett-Packard, which makes asimilar software called New Wave, contend that their productsare either protected under a 1985 license agreement, or usestandard features that copyright laws don't protect.</TEXT></DOC>